   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="entry">
            <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary01_0.jpg"/>
            <dateline>
               <placeName key="Annapolis, MD"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl002"
                  >Annapolis, Maryland, Camp Burnside November</placeName> —<date when="1861-11-22">
                  Friday, Thursday 22, 1861</date>
            </dateline>
            <p>
               <name type="weather ">This is a bright fair day</name>. We got up about seven,
                  <objectName type="food">breakfast</objectName>, company drill, dress parade,
               supper brought &amp; is quickly through &amp; evening. Visited over to see our sick —
                  <persName key="Henry Miller"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper100"
                  >Henry Miller</persName>, <persName>Hogan</persName> &amp; <persName
                  key="James A. Kelley"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper045"
                  >Kelly</persName> in the <placeName>hospital</placeName>. Sent them <objectName
                  type="food">tea and toast</objectName>. The <placeName>hospital</placeName>
               situation and the <placeName>hospital</placeName> arrangements are far from
               comfortable. Besides them lay <persName key="Charles Drainer"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper018"
                  >Charles Drainer,</persName> weakened down with a severe hemorrhage, &amp; not
               long for this world. He was with our <orgName>company</orgName> in the three months
               service &amp; was lately in <placeName key="Hagerstown, MD"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl042"
                  >Hagerstown.</placeName> He has been discharged in the service, went out into
                  <placeName>town</placeName> to inquire for <persName>Mrs. Monroe,</persName> but
               since he has moved away to take charge of a<placeName> school</placeName> at
                  <placeName key="Frederick, Maryland"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl038"
                  >Frederick.</placeName> His <persName> brother Harry </persName>has now charge of
               the seminary. <persName> Col. Hartshorne’s lady</persName> was here this evening. The
                  <persName>Col.</persName> returned from <placeName key="Washington, D.C."
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl091"
                  >Washington</placeName> this evening.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="entry">
            <pb n="2" facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary01_0.jpg"/>
            <dateline>
               <date when="1861-11-23">Saturday 23</date>
            </dateline>
            <p>This morning when we got up it was <name type="weather">rainin<name type="weather"/>g
                  and the <placeName>camp</placeName> was <name type="weather">wet and
                  dreary</name>.</name> I felt as if I was glad it<name type="Weather">
                  rained</name> to get relieved. But it cleared off about <time>ten o'clock</time>.
               There was regimental drill but as our <objectName type="weapon">muskets
               </objectName>were freshly marked, I got excused, but we were out for dress parade
               &amp; had a march in review. We had the pleasure of welcoming <persName
                  key="Seth Housel"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper071"
                  >Seth Housel </persName>back this afternoon, and this evening <persName
                  key="Jacob G. Beaver"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper003"
                  >Beaver </persName>returned, bringing all that we expected of him, <persName
                  key="George Shorkley"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper002"
                  >George Shorkley</persName> is lieutenant of the guard today. We had an
                  <objectName type="food">oyster pie</objectName> for dinner, but we were hurried
               &amp; didn't enjoy it.<objectName/>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="entry">
            <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary01_0.jpg"/>
            <dateline>
               <date when="1861-11-24">&amp;gt;Sunday 24</date>.</dateline>
            <p>The <name type="weather">day was gloomy</name> - sadly overcast - <name
                  type="weather">air windy &amp; this evening it commenced snowing.</name> We had a
               preaching by our Chaplain. "Rebellion is as the sin of witchcraft," the text. This
               afternoon, <persName key="George Shorkley"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper002"
                  >Shorkleley</persName>, <persName key="Jacob G. Beaver"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper003"
                  >Beaver</persName> &amp; I took a stroll through the <placeName key="Navy Yard"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl057"
                  >navy yard</placeName>, <placeName>town &amp; </placeName>
               <placeName>cemetery</placeName>. Everything has an air of decay. </p>
            <p xml:id="a2">The <placeName key="Navy Yard"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl057"
                  >navy yard </placeName>does not look like it did when I first saw it last spring.
               The old Battery looks natural enough. So the <placeName>Cemetery</placeName>. There
               are the graves of the <persName>Randalls</persName>, [?] &amp; many old familiar
               names. As we came out of the <placeName>cemetery</placeName>, we met an
                  <placeName>officer</placeName> with a [squad?] of men from the cavalry Regiment
               going to dig a grave. </p>
            <pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary02.jpg"/>
            <fw>
               <placeName key="Annapolis, MD"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl002"
                  >Anapolis Md</placeName>. <placeName key="Camp Union"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnp0l11"
                  >Camp Burnside</placeName>
               <lb/>
               <date> November Sunday 24 1861.</date>
            </fw>
            <p xml:id="a3">This evening,<persName key="Thomas Grier"
                  ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper076"
                  > Tom Grier </persName>and I went to the <placeName>Presbyterian
                  Church</placeName> &amp; came home through<name type="weather"> rain and
                  snow</name>. We saw several handsome ladies, one in particular. I got vaccinated
               yesterday, &amp; this evening it itches considerable I have two slight scars on my
               arm, but they are very slight.</p>
         </div>
